10 (1) receive a contribution;
11 (2) conduct a fund–raising event;
12 (3) PARTICIPATE IN A FUNDRAISING EVENT AS A FEATURED GUEST
13 OR SPEAKER OR IN ANOTHER ROLE INTENDED TO INCREASE ATTENDANCE AT OR
14 THE AMOUNT OF CONTRIBUTIONS RESULTING FROM THE FUNDRAISING EVENT;
15 [(3)] (4) solicit a contribution; or
16 [(4)] (5) deposit or use any contribution of money that was not deposited
17 prior to the session.
18 (c) An official described in subsection (a) of this section, or a person acting on
19 behalf of the official, is not subject to this section when engaged in activities solely related
20 to the official’s election to an elective federal or local office for which the official is a filed
21 candidate.
22 (d) Under the Public Financing Act, a gubernatorial ticket, during the year of the
23 election only, may accept eligible private contributions and any disbursement of funds by
24 the State Board that is based on the eligible private contributions.
25 (e) An official described in subsection (a) of this section, or a person acting on
26 behalf of the official, may deposit a contribution during the legislative session if the
27 contribution was made electronically before the start of the session.
28 (f) (1) As to a violation of this section, the campaign finance entity of the
29 official in violation is liable for a civil penalty as provided in § 13–604.1 of this title.
30 (2) A civil penalty imposed under this subsection shall be distributed to the
31 Fair Campaign Financing Fund established under § 15–103 of this article.

